{{Infobox NRHP | name =Academy of Music | nrhp_type = | designated_other1 = Virginia Landmarks Register | designated_other1_date = November 5, 1968<ref name=register>{{cite web|title=Virginia Landmarks Register|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources|accessdate=19 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053819/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|archive-date=2013-09-21|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> | designated_other1_number = 118-0001 | designated_other1_num_position = bottom | image = Academy of Music Lynchburg Nov 08-1.JPG | caption = Academy of Music, Lynchburg VA, November 2008 | location= 522—526 Main St., [[Lynchburg, Virginia]] | coordinates = {{coord|37|25|1|N|79|8|44|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Virginia#USA | area = | built =1904 | architect= [[Frye & Chesterman]] | architecture=[[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux Arts]] | added = June 11, 1969 | governing_body = Private | refnum=69000340<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref> }} The '''Academy of Music''' is a historic [[theatre]] building located in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]]. The three story theater was built 1904–05 in the [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux Arts style]] with a [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] interior. It was designed by [[Frye & Chesterman]]. It is one of the only surviving legitimate theaters of the turn-of-the-century period in Virginia. Some of the more notable European and American names to appear on its stage included [[Ignace Paderewski]], [[Anna Pavlova]], [[Sarah Bernhardt]], [[Alma Gluck]], [[DeWolf Hopper]], [[Otis Skinner]], [[John Drew, Jr.|John Drew]] and [[Mrs. Patrick Campbell]].<ref name=VAnom>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Lynchburg/118-0001_AcademyofMusic_1969_Final_Nomination.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Academy of Music|author=Virginia Historic Landmarks Commission Staff |date=April 1969|publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources}} and [http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Lynchburg/AcademyofMusic_photographs.htm ''Accompanying photo'']</ref> In 2008, the [[Lynchburg Academy of Fine Arts]] received a $245,000 [[Earmark (politics)|earmark]] from [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Bob Goodlatte]] from the Community Development Fund of the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]], for renovations to the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earmarks.omb.gov/2008-earmarks/earmark_289043.html|title=Appropriations Report Language – Conference|date=2008-11-21|work= Academy of Music earmark|publisher=Office of Management and Budget}}</ref>
It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1969.<ref name="nris"/>
